<subSubSection id="7CD73EBA5CD2E9128846D913DB74BA08" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="6F2DD4862479AB5B7013EA1B776A16AB" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F7B4FF0312C9FAB693AEE2432C3CA051" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
This new species resembles 
<taxonomicName id="A9EE6F8341CE67776F0CC7561C3E07E8" authorityName="Wang, Wang, Zhou &amp; Dai" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Idioscopus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Idioscopus furcaprocessus" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="furcaprocessus">
<emphasis id="1C0C72EECCB07278396A9E66383E7D56" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Idioscopus furcaprocessus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in general appearance, including having a yellow patch on the forewing clavus. The sinuate shaft of the aedeagus in lateral view is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="5A105CDC150DEEA74C10077385063BC7" genus="I." lsidName="I. confuscous" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" rank="species" species="confuscous">
<emphasis id="F1E4E282C78FB13C24272C06ECBB1BA2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">I. confuscous</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Pruthi) (see Viraktamath, 1980: fig. 15), 
<taxonomicName id="CFFBE4883C6CBB4FD6A53F053B48683B" genus="I." lsidName="I. bihamulus" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" rank="species" species="bihamulus">
<emphasis id="E44AE6107EE67D6D07F2294A1A9554BF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">I. bihamulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="C2FEFC680BB6866A194588F3A62F1837" genus="I." lsidName="I. recurvatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" rank="species" species="recurvatus">
<emphasis id="C78A41DDA03244AF44C9995AF22DAD19" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">I. recurvatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="F8B976136932C369A57998A68A4805D2" genus="I." lsidName="I. nitellicus" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" rank="species" species="nitellicus">
<emphasis id="B3F752069EAFA7DD6B65049B75412F55" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">I. nitellicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but it differs from these and other species in having an unpaired, ventral, spine-like process proximad of the midlength of the shaft.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5A70D1D970ADC2EE17DE1BA9776108DC" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" type="description">
<paragraph id="E7E0977123393B5E60B70245E636FE14" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D5D993C78A6B227839DA62F9B84F77F3" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis id="1C668894C0EE2D6E36A15ABB2BFC24F8" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis id="C1E258315DE5B1E1C54C5F51BF5E3368" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Coloration</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
General color reddish brown. Crown yellowish with darker reddish-brown markings; eyes yellowish (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E3FE085376C885246A4527ED106471BB" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Idioscopus ventrispinus sp. nov. male A habitus, dorsal view B face C head and thorax, lateral view D forewing E genital capsule, lateral view F pygofer dorsal view G connective and style, dorsal view H aedeagus, lateral view I aedeagus ventral view. Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.76731.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671693" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">2A-C</figureCitation>
). Pronotum and mesonotum (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="31CDF07A7D0D0799E6A001D2F3F2A96F" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Idioscopus ventrispinus sp. nov. male A habitus, dorsal view B face C head and thorax, lateral view D forewing E genital capsule, lateral view F pygofer dorsal view G connective and style, dorsal view H aedeagus, lateral view I aedeagus ventral view. Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.76731.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671693" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">2A</figureCitation>
) reddish brown, mesonotum paler with yellowish hue. Face (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="95E43401636CF09CB7069469DB1D654F" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Idioscopus ventrispinus sp. nov. male A habitus, dorsal view B face C head and thorax, lateral view D forewing E genital capsule, lateral view F pygofer dorsal view G connective and style, dorsal view H aedeagus, lateral view I aedeagus ventral view. Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.76731.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671693" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">2B</figureCitation>
) greenish yellow with frontoclypeus and anteclypeus pale reddish brown; male antennae with apical disc, black. Mesepimeron (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="EDC908CE5EC5D2A61A674D89C9BDAB8B" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Idioscopus ventrispinus sp. nov. male A habitus, dorsal view B face C head and thorax, lateral view D forewing E genital capsule, lateral view F pygofer dorsal view G connective and style, dorsal view H aedeagus, lateral view I aedeagus ventral view. Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.76731.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671693" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">2C</figureCitation>
) with black patch. Forewing clavus (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5235950C470CDA8B9A1C4BEE95B4330E" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Idioscopus ventrispinus sp. nov. male A habitus, dorsal view B face C head and thorax, lateral view D forewing E genital capsule, lateral view F pygofer dorsal view G connective and style, dorsal view H aedeagus, lateral view I aedeagus ventral view. Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.76731.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671693" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">2A</figureCitation>
) with large, lemon-yellow patch bordered with dark reddish brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A1E85F9214C30006DF54A315E2A742F5" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
External features as in generic description with head and thorax shagreen; male antennae with apical disc (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B71867B237CFB8FA7BEF40FB521CBA22" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Idioscopus ventrispinus sp. nov. male A habitus, dorsal view B face C head and thorax, lateral view D forewing E genital capsule, lateral view F pygofer dorsal view G connective and style, dorsal view H aedeagus, lateral view I aedeagus ventral view. Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.76731.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671693" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">2A-C</figureCitation>
); forewing (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="EDB2FAAE8CC5440B2F2B936FAC2BB43A" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Idioscopus ventrispinus sp. nov. male A habitus, dorsal view B face C head and thorax, lateral view D forewing E genital capsule, lateral view F pygofer dorsal view G connective and style, dorsal view H aedeagus, lateral view I aedeagus ventral view. Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.76731.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671693" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">2D</figureCitation>
) with two subapical cells, inner subapical open.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6701461285FECA8118C948025932E09C" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis id="C561779FB5FAECA33F8326BD6147E710" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis id="F122F49248F8C6E5C9F815254A4D2543" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Male genitalia</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Male pygofer (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="D5BED36A23BC21A04B7BC43D99EAA758" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Idioscopus ventrispinus sp. nov. male A habitus, dorsal view B face C head and thorax, lateral view D forewing E genital capsule, lateral view F pygofer dorsal view G connective and style, dorsal view H aedeagus, lateral view I aedeagus ventral view. Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.76731.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671693" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">2E, F</figureCitation>
) conically rounded apically, without ventral process; anal collar thin, upturned apically; dorsoanterior apodemes well developed. Anal tube (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="ECF94C8F4DEB483B904E698974C97D0F" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Idioscopus ventrispinus sp. nov. male A habitus, dorsal view B face C head and thorax, lateral view D forewing E genital capsule, lateral view F pygofer dorsal view G connective and style, dorsal view H aedeagus, lateral view I aedeagus ventral view. Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.76731.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671693" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">2E</figureCitation>
) long. Subgenital plates (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="DBA347590684F7EB674C2843D0DF745C" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Idioscopus ventrispinus sp. nov. male A habitus, dorsal view B face C head and thorax, lateral view D forewing E genital capsule, lateral view F pygofer dorsal view G connective and style, dorsal view H aedeagus, lateral view I aedeagus ventral view. Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.76731.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671693" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">2E</figureCitation>
) broader in distal one-third in lateral view, longer than pygofer, sharply upturned in basal third, with long hair-like marginal setae distally. Connective (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5A0282716149F17501047D41F49DD164" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Idioscopus ventrispinus sp. nov. male A habitus, dorsal view B face C head and thorax, lateral view D forewing E genital capsule, lateral view F pygofer dorsal view G connective and style, dorsal view H aedeagus, lateral view I aedeagus ventral view. Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.76731.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671693" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">2G</figureCitation>
) Y-shaped, broad, with short stem. Style apophysis (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="20231790942CFCA99EC01548894AD33D" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Idioscopus ventrispinus sp. nov. male A habitus, dorsal view B face C head and thorax, lateral view D forewing E genital capsule, lateral view F pygofer dorsal view G connective and style, dorsal view H aedeagus, lateral view I aedeagus ventral view. Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.76731.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671693" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">2G</figureCitation>
) narrowed to apex with weakly serrated inner margin. Aedeagus (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="949444012C0D97637607F2C35AF2B3F2" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Idioscopus ventrispinus sp. nov. male A habitus, dorsal view B face C head and thorax, lateral view D forewing E genital capsule, lateral view F pygofer dorsal view G connective and style, dorsal view H aedeagus, lateral view I aedeagus ventral view. Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.76731.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671693" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">2H, I</figureCitation>
) with shaft laterally compressed, broad in basal half then narrowed and slightly sinuate distally to acute apex in lateral view, with one pair of subapical bifid processes, each fork unequal, an unpaired ventral spine-like process proximad of midlength; dorsal apodeme laterally compressed, distally expanded in lateral view and laterally expanded distally in ventral view.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8A50707838691D5FDF8BAD15FC9C5992" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis id="70D66C211DB8F12D229FE102EBBE1D5A" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis id="F7AEAFF926981200708E9EF67A15E543" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Female genitalia</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Posterior margin of sternite VII (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="4CE748D11C1A953DED87C109B9664B79" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Ovipositor. Female. A-E Idioscopus bihamulus sp. nov. F-J Idioscopus ventrispinus sp. nov. A, F sternite VII B, G first valvula C, H apex of first valvula D, I second valvula E, J apex of second valvula." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.76731.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671694" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">3F</figureCitation>
) slightly produced medially. Valvulae as in Figure 
<figureCitation id="CC42B78E25BCADF1F6F59810E0C2B68F" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Ovipositor. Female. A-E Idioscopus bihamulus sp. nov. F-J Idioscopus ventrispinus sp. nov. A, F sternite VII B, G first valvula C, H apex of first valvula D, I second valvula E, J apex of second valvula." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.76731.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671694" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">3G-J</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2B1BB08AF1DF479F315F4C35275D146E" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" type="description">
<paragraph id="EB472427AFD5BD054A43A2BCDD05614F" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Measurements (mm).</paragraph>
<paragraph id="256963EEB4D7DED3C48298059CD04350" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Male: body length including tegmina 4.50-4.95. Medial length of crown 0.18-0.22, width 1.55-1.60. Distance from ocellus to eyes 0.15-0.20. Medial length of pronotum 0.45-0.48, width 1.35-1.45; scutellum length 0.50-0.55, width 0.65-0.70. Female: body length 4.60-5.20 including tegmina.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="898C88E3BD695169983B61FED29BCA62" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="CAF378CA9D104417E948FC747051D3A0" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8A6F099CD65DA78599AD56129C31A65B" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
The new species name is derived from the words 
<emphasis id="38B7CB6905A8542007A591F255832063" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">ventri</emphasis>
- and 
<emphasis id="5881F24B410A04D2D92C9709896C2E54" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">spinus</emphasis>
, referring to the ventral spine-like process of the aedeagal shaft.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
